This is where students finally understand:

Browser
#     ↓
# Fetch API
#     ↓
Server
#     ↓
# JSON Response
#     ↓
Browser

This module directly prepares them for:

Express.js
# Login Systems
# REST APIs
# Full Stack Development
# --------------------------------------------------
# MODULE 5 : FETCH API & JSON DATA EXCHANGE
# --------------------------------------------------

st.title("🌐 Module 5 : Fetch API & JSON Data Exchange")

st.success("""
Learning Outcomes

✅ Understand APIs

✅ Understand Client-Server Communication

✅ Understand Fetch API

✅ Work with GET Requests

✅ Work with POST Requests

✅ Understand JSON Data Exchange

✅ Connect Browser with Server
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# INTRODUCTION
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("1️⃣ What is an API?")

st.markdown("""
API stands for:

Application Programming Interface

An API acts as a bridge between two applications.

Examples:

📦 Amazon Product API

🌦 Weather API

📍 Maps API

🤖 AI API

🎓 Student Portal API
""")

st.markdown("""

```text
Client

↓

API

↓

Server


""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# REAL WORLD ANALOGY
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("2️⃣ Restaurant Analogy")

st.markdown("""

Imagine visiting a restaurant.

You don't enter the kitchen.

Instead:

Customer

↓

Waiter

↓

Kitchen

↓

Waiter

↓

Customer

The Waiter acts like an API.
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# CLIENT SERVER MODEL
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("3️⃣ Client-Server Architecture")

st.markdown("""

Browser (Client)

↓

Request

↓

Server

↓

Response

↓

Browser

""")

st.info("""
Client = Browser

Server = Express.js

Communication = API
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# WHAT IS FETCH API?
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("4️⃣ What is Fetch API?")

st.markdown("""
Fetch API allows JavaScript to communicate with servers.
""")

st.code("""

fetch("https://example.com")

""", language="javascript")

st.success("""
Fetch sends a request to a server.
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# SIMPLE FETCH
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("5️⃣ Simple Fetch Example")

st.code("""

fetch(

"https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users"

)

.then(response => response.json())

.then(data => console.log(data));

""", language="javascript")

st.markdown("""
This requests user data from a server.
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# WHY JSON?
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("6️⃣ Why JSON?")

st.markdown("""

JavaScript Object

↓

JSON

↓

Internet

↓

JSON

↓

JavaScript Object

""")

st.code("""

{
"name":"John",
"course":"BCA"
}

""", language="json")

# --------------------------------------------------
# GET REQUEST
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("7️⃣ GET Request")

st.markdown("""
GET is used to retrieve data.
""")

st.code("""

fetch("/students")

""", language="javascript")

st.success("""
GET = Read Data
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# REAL EXAMPLES
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("8️⃣ GET Request Examples")

examples = {

"Application":[

    "Student Portal",

    "Amazon",

    "Netflix",

    "Hospital",

    "Travel"

],

"GET Request":[

    "Get Students",

    "Get Products",

    "Get Movies",

    "Get Patients",

    "Get Flights"

# ]

# }

st.table(examples)

# --------------------------------------------------
# POST REQUEST
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("9️⃣ POST Request")

st.markdown("""
POST sends data to a server.
""")

st.code("""

fetch(

"/login",

{

method:"POST"

}

)

""", language="javascript")

st.success("""
POST = Send Data
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# LOGIN EXAMPLE
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("🔟 Login Request Example")

st.code("""

fetch(

"/login",

{

method:"POST",

headers:{

"Content-Type":"application/json"

},

body:JSON.stringify({

username:"admin",

password:"1234"

})

}

);

""", language="javascript")

st.markdown("""

Username

↓

Password

↓

JSON

↓

Server

""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# SERVER RESPONSE
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("1️⃣1️⃣ JSON Response")

st.code("""

{

"success":true,

"message":"Login Successful"

}

""", language="json")

st.success("""
Server sends JSON back to the browser.
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# RESPONSE PROCESSING
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("1️⃣2️⃣ Reading Response")

st.code("""

const response =

await fetch("/login");

const data =

await response.json();

console.log(data);

""", language="javascript")

st.markdown("""
Response

↓

JSON

↓

JavaScript Object
""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# COMPLETE FLOW
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("1️⃣3️⃣ Complete Flow")

st.markdown("""

User Clicks Login

↓

JavaScript Creates Object

↓

JSON.stringify()

↓

Fetch API

↓

Express Server

↓

Validation

↓

JSON Response

↓

response.json()

↓

Display Result

""")

# --------------------------------------------------
# INTERACTIVE EXPLANATION
# --------------------------------------------------

st.header("1️⃣4️⃣ Request Types")

